(44, 27, 5, 44, 13, 13, 13, 'Pamphylia', 'Journey Through Pamphylia', 'Both passages emphasize the geographical region of Pamphylia, highlighting its significance in Paul''s travels. The mention of Pamphylia in both contexts connects the journeys of Paul and his companions.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 5, 44, 2, 10, 10, 'Pamphylia', 'Geographical Connection in Acts', 'Both passages emphasize Pamphylia as a significant location. Acts 27:5 mentions Pamphylia in the context of travel, while Acts 2:10 lists it among regions represented at Pentecost.', 'keyword', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 5, 44, 15, 23, 23, 'Cilicia', 'Connection through Cilicia', 'Both passages emphasize Cilicia as a significant region. In Acts 15:23, Cilicia is mentioned in the context of the early church''s outreach to Gentiles, while Acts 27:5 describes a journey that includes sailing over the sea of Cilicia.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 5, 48, 1, 21, 21, 'Cilicia', 'Geographical Connection in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the region of Cilicia, linking Paul''s travels in Acts to his later ministry in Galatians. This connection highlights the geographical continuity in Paul''s journeys.', 'keyword', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 6, 44, 28, 11, 11, 'ship of Alexandria', 'Journey by Ship of Alexandria', 'Both passages emphasize the use of a ship of Alexandria, linking the journey of Paul to Italy. This connection highlights the continuity of travel and the specific vessel involved in the narrative.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 6, 44, 6, 9, 9, 'Alexandria', 'Connection through Alexandria', 'Both passages mention Alexandria, linking the city to significant events in the early church. This connection highlights the role of Alexandria in the spread of Christianity and the diverse backgrounds of its followers.', 'keyword', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 6, 44, 18, 24, 24, 'ship of Alexandria', 'Connection through Alexandria', 'This connection highlights the significance of Alexandria as a cultural and geographical link in the narrative. Both passages mention Alexandria, indicating its importance in the early Christian movement.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 6, 44, 27, 1, 1, NULL, 'Journey to Italy', 'Both passages emphasize the journey to Italy, highlighting the involvement of Paul and the centurion Julius. The mention of sailing into Italy in both verses connects the narrative of Paul''s voyage.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 7, 44, 27, 21, 21, 'sailed under Crete', 'Journey and Warning Connection', 'This connection highlights the journey of Paul and his warning to the crew. Both passages emphasize the challenges faced during the voyage and the consequences of not heeding Paul''s advice.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 7, 44, 2, 11, 11, 'Crete', 'Connection of Crete and Speech', 'This connection highlights the mention of Crete in both passages. Acts 27:7 refers to sailing under Crete, while Acts 2:11 includes Cretes among those hearing the works of God.', 'keyword', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 7, 44, 27, 12, 13, 'sailed under Crete', 'Journey and Navigation Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the journey of sailing and the challenges faced at sea. The mention of sailing under Crete in the source verse connects to the decision to sail close by Crete in the target passage.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 7, 56, 1, 5, 5, 'under Crete', 'Sailing and Ministry in Crete', 'This connection highlights the geographical link between Crete in both passages. Acts describes the journey under Crete, while Titus mentions the establishment of order in Crete, suggesting a continuity in Paul''s mission.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 7, 56, 1, 12, 12, NULL, 'Connection Between Cretans and Sailing', 'This connection highlights the slow progress in Acts 27:7 and the description of the Cretans as ''slow bellies'' in Titus 1:12. Both passages emphasize a theme of slowness, suggesting a parallel in behavior and experience.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 7, 44, 27, 4, 4, NULL, 'Sailing Challenges in Acts', 'Both passages emphasize the difficulties faced while sailing due to contrary winds. The mention of sailing under different locations highlights the ongoing struggle against unfavorable conditions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 9, 3, 23, 27, 29, 'when sailing was now dangerous', 'Connection of Timing and Warning', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of timing in relation to important events. In Acts, Paul warns of dangerous sailing after a specific time, while Leviticus outlines the Day of Atonement, a critical time for affliction and atonement.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 9, 4, 29, 7, 7, 'the fast was now already past', 'Connection of Fasting and Danger', 'This connection highlights the theme of fasting as a time of danger and reflection. In Acts, the mention of ''the fast'' indicates a period of spiritual significance, while in Numbers, the command to ''afflict your souls'' during the fast suggests a similar focus on self-examination and caution.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 9, 3, 16, 29, 31, 'the fast was now already past', 'Connection of Time and Atonement', 'This connection highlights the significance of timing in both passages. In Acts, the mention of ''the fast'' indicates a period of reflection and caution, paralleling Leviticus, where the Day of Atonement is a time for affliction and cleansing.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 10, 27, 2, 30, 30, 'this voyage will be with hurt', 'Perception of Danger and Wisdom', 'This connection highlights the theme of perceiving danger and the importance of wisdom in understanding circumstances. In Acts, the warning of impending harm reflects a discernment similar to Daniel''s revelation of secrets, emphasizing the need for insight in critical situations.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 10, 30, 3, 7, 7, 'this voyage will be with hurt', 'Divine Warning and Revelation', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine warning. In Acts 27:10, the warning of impending danger reflects the idea in Amos 3:7 that God reveals His secrets to His prophets, indicating that God communicates crucial information to guide His people.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 10, 44, 27, 20, 26, 'this voyage will be with hurt', 'Paul''s Warning and Assurance', 'This connection highlights Paul''s initial warning about the voyage''s danger and his later reassurance to the crew. Both passages emphasize the themes of impending harm and the preservation of life amidst peril.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 10, 44, 27, 41, 44, 'this voyage will be with hurt', 'Voyage and Survival Connection', 'This connection highlights the perilous situation described in both passages. The warning of ''hurt and much damage'' in the source verse foreshadows the shipwreck and subsequent struggle for survival in the target passage.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 10, 19, 25, 14, 14, NULL, 'Fear and Divine Guidance', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine insight in both passages. In Acts, the warning of impending danger suggests a need for reverence and caution, while Psalms emphasizes that those who fear the Lord receive His guidance and covenant.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 10, 1, 41, 16, 25, 'much damage, not only of the lading and ship, but also of our lives', 'Warnings of Impending Danger', 'This connection highlights the theme of forewarning about impending peril. In Acts, Paul perceives danger to lives, while in Genesis, Joseph interprets Pharaoh''s dreams as a warning of future famine that will affect many lives.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 10, 1, 41, 38, 39, 'I perceive that this voyage will be with hurt', 'Wisdom in Crisis Situations', 'This connection highlights the theme of discernment in critical situations. In Acts, Paul perceives impending danger, while in Genesis, Joseph is recognized for his wisdom in interpreting Pharaoh''s dreams.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 11, 26, 33, 4, 4, 'believed the master and the owner', 'Warning and Consequences', 'This connection highlights the theme of heeding warnings. In Acts, the centurion disregards Paul''s warning, paralleling Ezekiel''s message about the consequences of ignoring the trumpet''s sound.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 11, 26, 3, 17, 18, 'more than those things which were spoken by Paul', 'Authority and Warning', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of heeding warnings from authoritative voices. In Acts, the centurion prioritizes the advice of the ship''s master over Paul''s warning, while Ezekiel is tasked with warning the wicked, highlighting the consequences of ignoring such warnings.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 11, 58, 11, 7, 7, 'believed the master and the owner', 'Faith and Belief in Action', 'This connection highlights the theme of belief in authority. In Acts, the centurion believes the ship''s master over Paul''s warning, while in Hebrews, Noah acts on God''s warning, demonstrating faith in unseen outcomes.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 11, 20, 27, 12, 12, 'believed the master and the owner', 'Prudence and Belief in Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of discernment in decision-making. In Acts, the centurion''s belief in the ship''s master over Paul''s warning reflects a lack of prudence, paralleling Proverbs'' warning about the simple being punished for ignoring foresight.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 11, 44, 27, 21, 21, NULL, 'Paul''s Warning Ignored', 'This connection highlights the consequences of ignoring Paul''s advice. In Acts 27:11, the centurion''s belief in the ship''s master leads to a decision that results in harm, which Paul later points out in Acts 27:21.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 11, 2, 9, 20, 21, 'believed the master and the owner', 'Belief in Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of belief in authority figures. In Acts, the centurion believes the master of the ship, while in Exodus, those who feared the word of the Lord acted accordingly, showing a similar response to authority.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 11, 12, 6, 10, 10, 'believed the master and the owner', 'Belief in Warnings', 'This connection highlights the theme of belief in warnings given by authoritative figures. In both passages, individuals respond to guidance from those they consider knowledgeable, leading to their preservation and safety.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 12, 19, 107, 30, 30, NULL, 'Connection of Desired Haven', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a ''haven'' as a place of safety and rest. Acts 27:12 discusses the desire to reach a suitable haven, while Psalms 107:30 describes the joy of arriving at a desired haven.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 12, 44, 27, 8, 8, NULL, 'Connection of Locations in Acts', 'Both passages emphasize the geographical context of the journey, specifically mentioning locations related to Crete. The mention of ''The fair havens'' in Acts 27:8 sets the stage for the subsequent discussion about the decision to move to Phenice in Acts 27:12.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 13, 18, 37, 17, 17, 'south wind', 'Connection of the South Wind', 'Both passages emphasize the south wind''s calming effect. In Acts, the south wind facilitates sailing, while in Job, it quiets the earth, suggesting a theme of tranquility associated with this wind.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 13, 19, 78, 26, 26, 'south wind', 'Connection of Winds in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the role of winds in both passages. Acts 27:13 mentions a south wind, while Psalms 78:26 refers to the south wind as part of God''s power.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 13, 22, 4, 16, 16, 'south wind', 'Connection of Winds in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the imagery of winds in both passages. In Acts, the ''south wind'' signifies favorable conditions for sailing, while in Song of Solomon, the ''south'' wind is invited to blow upon the garden, symbolizing desire and abundance.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 13, 42, 12, 55, 55, 'south wind', 'Connection of South Wind Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of the south wind as a sign of impending weather conditions. In Acts, the south wind indicates favorable sailing conditions, while in Luke, it signifies the approach of heat.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 14, 41, 4, 37, 37, NULL, 'Storm Imagery in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the occurrence of a great storm that threatens the safety of those on the ship. The tempestuous wind in Acts 27:14, called Euroclydon, parallels the great storm in Mark 4:37, highlighting the perilous nature of maritime journeys in biblical narratives.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 14, 19, 107, 25, 27, 'tempestuous wind', 'Connection of Storm Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the power of a storm, with Acts mentioning a ''tempestuous wind'' and Psalms describing a ''stormy wind.'' This connection highlights the tumultuous nature of the sea and the distress it causes to those caught in it.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 14, 2, 14, 21, 27, NULL, 'Connection of Winds and Waters', 'Both passages emphasize the role of strong winds in controlling the waters. In Acts, the tempestuous wind Euroclydon arises, while in Exodus, a strong east wind divides the sea. This connection highlights the power of divine intervention through natural elements.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 14, 26, 27, 26, 26, 'tempestuous wind', 'Connection of Storm Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the destructive power of winds at sea. The ''tempestuous wind'' in Acts and the ''east wind'' in Ezekiel illustrate the chaos and danger faced by those on the waters.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 14, 32, 1, 3, 5, 'tempestuous wind', 'Storms and Divine Intervention', 'Both passages emphasize a tempestuous wind that arises at sea, indicating divine intervention in the lives of those on the ships. In Acts, the wind is called Euroclydon, while in Jonah, it is described as a great wind sent by the Lord.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 14, 40, 8, 24, 24, NULL, 'Connection of Tempests in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize a ''great tempest'' affecting ships, illustrating the theme of divine intervention during storms. The presence of a tempest in both accounts highlights the challenges faced by those at sea.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 15, 44, 27, 27, 27, 'let her drive', 'Ship''s Direction and Control', 'Both passages emphasize the ship''s lack of control during the storm. In Acts 27:15, the ship was ''let her drive,'' indicating a loss of direction, while in Acts 27:27, they were ''driven up and down,'' further illustrating their helplessness at sea.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 15, 59, 3, 4, 4, NULL, 'Connection of Ship Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of ships being driven by external forces. Acts 27:15 describes a ship unable to resist the wind, while James 3:4 illustrates how ships, despite their size, are directed by a small helm. This connection highlights the contrast between external control and internal guidance.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 17, 44, 27, 29, 29, 'fearing lest they should fall', 'Fear of Shipwreck', 'Both passages emphasize the fear of danger at sea, with the crew taking precautions to avoid disaster. The actions of undergirding the ship and casting anchors reflect their concern for safety amidst perilous conditions.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 17, 44, 27, 26, 26, 'driven', 'Journey Through Perilous Waters', 'Both passages emphasize the ship''s precarious situation. The mention of being ''driven'' in the first passage connects to the necessity of being ''cast upon a certain island'' in the second, highlighting the urgency of their circumstances.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 27, 17, 44, 27, 41, 41, 'undergirding the ship', 'Shipwreck and Undergirding Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the ship''s struggle against the sea. The act of undergirding the ship in the first passage reflects the desperate measures taken to prevent disaster, which culminates in the ship running aground in the second passage.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
